04336nam a22006135i 9780823293520DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232935207 a10.1515/97808232935202doi  a(DE-B1597)566091  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0000002bisacsh1 aMalabou, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Should We Do with Our Brain? /cCatherine Malabou. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (120 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator’s Note -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Plasticity and Flexibility— For a Consciousness of the Brain -- t1 Plasticity’s Fields of Action -- t2 The Central Power in Crisis -- t3 ‘‘You Are Your Synapses’’ -- tConclusion: Toward a Biological Alter-Globalism -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent neuroscience, in replacing the old model of the brain as a single centralized source of control, has emphasized “plasticity,” the quality by which our brains develop and change throughout the course of our lives. Our brains exist as historical products, developing in interaction with themselves and with their surroundings. Hence there is a thin line between the organization of the nervous system and the political and social organization that both conditions and is conditioned by human experience. Looking carefully at contemporary neuroscience, it is hard not to notice that the new way of talking about the brain mirrors the management discourse of the neo-liberal capitalist world in which we now live, with its talk of decentralization, networks, and flexibility. Consciously or unconsciously, science cannot but echo the world in which it takes place. In the neo-liberal world, “plasticity” can be equated with “flexibility”—a term that has become a buzzword in economics and management theory. The plastic brain would thus represent just another style of power, which, although less centralized, is still a means of control. In this book, Catherine Malabou develops a second, more radical meaning for plasticity. Not only does plasticity allow our brains to adapt to existing circumstances, it opens a margin of freedom to intervene, to change those very circumstances. Such an understanding opens up a newly transformative aspect of the neurosciences. In insisting on this proximity between the neurosciences and the social sciences, Malabou applies to the brain Marx’s well-known phrase about history: people make their own brains, but they do not know it. This book is a summons to such knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aJeannerod, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823293520423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823293520/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK